05510nam a22007935i 9781487514167DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875141677 a10.3138/97814875141672doi  a(DE-B1597)525756  a(OCoLC)1089195402  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a841/.12231 aStone, Charles Russell, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Roman de toute chevalerie :bReading Alexander Romance in Late Medieval England /cCharles Russell Stone. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Reading and Reconstructing the Anglo-Norman Alexander -- tChapter One. Alexander Romance in Twelfth-Century Europe -- tChapter Two. Alexander in Anglo-Norman England: The Latin Texts -- tChapter Three. The Roman de toute chevalerie: Sources, Influences, and Innovations -- tChapter Four. The Two Deaths of Alexander in Cambridge, Trinity College MS O. 9. 34 -- tChapter Five. Paris, Bibliothèque Nationale MS 24364: Alexander, Chivalry, and the Wars of Edward I -- tChapter Six. Moralizing Alexander in Durham Cathedral Library MS C.IV.27B -- tChapter Seven. From Anglo-Norman to Middle English Alexander Romance -- tAfterword: The Advent of the Continental Alexander -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe medieval reception of Alexander the Great inspired a complicated literary corpus not simply because it involved so many source-texts and languages, but because it incorporated such diverse perspectives on the conqueror. Beginning with a discussion of the evolution of this corpus, this book examines the manuscripts, readership, and historical contexts of the earliest surviving Alexander romance in England, Thomas de Kent’s Anglo-Norman Roman de toute chevalerie. To shed light on the origins and treatment of this romance, Charles Russell Stone reads each manuscript within the contexts of its production, scribal interpolations, and patronage and readership in the thirteenth and fourteenth centuries. While Thomas recalls a range of attitudes towards his protagonist in the late twelfth century, when the recovery of classical histories and composition of vernacular romance informed conflicting attitudes towards Alexander’s legacy, scribes and readers of his poem appropriated it as a continuing commentary on power, politics, and the relevance of the Alexander legend in their own time. Each of the three major manuscripts of Thomas’s poem thus offers a unique text informed by unique literary and political contexts, which this book situates within the ongoing debate over Alexander’s reception as a paradigm of imperial authority or failure in late medieval England.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAlexander the Great.  aAnglo-Norman literature.  aclassical tradition.  acodicology.  aliterature and politics.  amedieval romance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz978311061036908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toro